the adult male black-winged lovebird has a red forehead and a ring of red feathers around its eyes. The tail is black tipped and feathers below the tail show a yellowish colour. The rump and feathers above the tail are light green. In the male, feathers under the wing are typically black, and in the female the feathers under the wing are typically greenish or brownish black. Both sexes have a red beak and gray feet. Habitat The natural distribution for the black-winged lovebird is typically from southern Eritrea to southwestern Ethiopia, and they normally live in either high plains or mountainous regions. Behavior Food and feeding Sunflower seeds, corn, apples and mission figs are typical of an Abyssinian lovebird diet. Breeding The black-winged lovebird nests in a tree cavity. The eggs are white and there are usually three or four eggs in a clutch. The female incubates the eggs for 23 days, and the chicks fledge from the nest about 45 days after hatching. Black-winged lovebirds reproduce from March to November; nesting takes place in tree hollows, crevices in walls, and potentially in weavers' nests. The nests are furnished with a combination of plant debris and feathers. Status Widespread and common throughout its range, the black-winged lovebird is evaluated as Least Concern on the IUCN Red List of Threatened Species. Aviculture In aviculture the black-winged lovebird has not become well established as a breeding bird, although it can tolerate cold weather. Breeding in aviculture is on a small scale, so it is an uncommon pet. Taxonomy A holotype of Psittacus taranta Stanley (Salt's Voy. to Abyssinia, 1814, App IV, p.lii(=52)), an adult male, is held in the vertebrate zoology collection of National Museums Liverpool at World Museum, with accession number NML-VZ D704. The specimen was collected in Taranta Pass, Acchele Guzai District, Eritrea in 1809-10 by Henry Salt. The specimen came to the Liverpool national collection via the 13th Earl of Derby's collection, which was bequeathed to the people of Liverpool in 1851. References \"Species factsheet: Agapornis taranta\". BirdLife International (2008).", "shortSummary": "The black-winged lovebird (Agapornis taranta) also known as Abyssinian lovebird is a mainly green bird of the parrot family. At about 16.5…", "imageUrl": "https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/d3/Agapornis_taranta_-_Bergpapagei_-_Wildfarbig_-_Deutscher_Kanarien-_und_Vogelz%C3%BCchterbund_%28DKB%29_-_Vogelbund_-_Johann_Alexi.jpg/960px-Agapornis_taranta_-_Bergpapagei_-_Wildfarbig_-_Deutscher_Kanarien-_und_Vogelz%C3%BCchterbund_%28DKB%29_-_Vogelbund_-_Johann_Alexi.jpg", "kingdomId": "taxonomy-kingdom-animalia", "phylumId": "taxonomy-phylum-chordata", "classId": "taxonomy-class-aves", "genusId": "taxonomy-genus-agapornis", "speciesId": "taxonomy-species-agapornis-taranta", "taxonomyIds": {"kingdom": "taxonomy-kingdom-animalia", "phylum": "taxonomy-phylum-chordata", "class": "taxonomy-class-aves", "genus": "taxonomy-genus-agapornis", "species": "taxonomy-species-agapornis-taranta"}, "expandable": true, "x": -55.38, "y": 725.8, "z": -768.86}], "links": [{"key": "bird-black-winged-lovebird-5a91eb34__belongs_to_species__taxonomy-species-agapornis-taranta", "source": "bird-black-winged-lovebird-5a91eb34", "target": "taxonomy-species-agapornis-taranta", "relation": "belongs_to_species", "label": "属于种", "evidence": "依据 birds.csv 中的种字段补充。"}, {"key": "taxonomy-species-agapornis-taranta__belongs_to_genus__taxonomy-genus-agapornis", "source": "taxonomy-species-agapornis-taranta", "target": "taxonomy-genus-agapornis", "relation": "belongs_to_genus", "label": "属于属", "evidence": "依据 birds.csv 分类字段补充：Black-winged lovebird 属于属 Agapornis。"}]}
